<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="356" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,638,1470,1730]" pageId="13" pageNumber="356">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,279,1470,1491]" pageId="13" pageNumber="356">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The tarsal claws of this species are bifid. Also, each elytron is yellow, with a sutural dark stripe (
<figureCitation box="[261,328,1523,1544]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[197,228,1687,1706]" captionTargetBox="[179,1188,443,1668]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[175,1190,441,1670]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 2. Triarius species, dorsal habitus. A) T. pini, male, B) T. pini, female, C) T. trivittatus, D) T. nigroflavus, male, E) T. nigroflavus, female, F) T. melanolomatus, G) T. lividus, H) T. texanus, I) T. novoleonis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3445865" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3445865/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="356">Fig. 2c</figureCitation>
), a posthumeral dark stripe, and a dark, short, oblique, median, subbasal stripe. Taken together, these characters distinguish this from all other New World species of Scelidites. Specimens measure 4.0– 
<quantity box="[280,354,1629,1650]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.1" pageId="13" pageNumber="356" unit="mm" value="7.1">7.1 mm</quantity>
in length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="356" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,638,1470,1730]" lastBlockId="13.[685,1172,193,719]" pageId="13" pageNumber="356">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,453,1656,1677]" pageId="13" pageNumber="356">Type Material Examined.</emphasis>
We located four specimens from the type series in the Horn Collection (
<collectionCode box="[228,284,1709,1730]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:33791" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:33791" name="Museum of Comparative Zoology" pageId="13" pageNumber="356" type="Museum">MCZ</collectionCode>
). One of them, a male, bears the label “ 
<typeStatus box="[696,797,194,215]" pageId="13" pageNumber="356">LectoType</typeStatus>
3796.” However, it is not clear who added the 
<typeStatus box="[788,875,220,241]" pageId="13" pageNumber="356">lectotype</typeStatus>
label to the specimen, and, to our knowledge, a 
<typeStatus box="[865,952,247,268]" pageId="13" pageNumber="356">lectotype</typeStatus>
designation has never been published. In any case, this specimen is now designated as the 
<typeStatus box="[858,945,300,321]" pageId="13" pageNumber="356">lectotype</typeStatus>
for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Horn" authorityYear="1893" box="[988,1105,300,321]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Triarius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="356" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trivittatus">
<emphasis box="[988,1105,300,321]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="356">T. trivittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[685,1172,193,719]" box="[709,1136,326,348]" pageId="13" pageNumber="356">
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="2416598818" box="[709,1136,326,348]" location="Pinal Mountains" pageId="13" pageNumber="356" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Arizona" typeStatus="holotype">
